{
  "question": "A solid, prismatic bar of Terfenol-D, with initial clamped length $L_0 = 0.25~\text{m}$, width $w = 0.020~\text{m}$, and thickness $h = 0.0050~\text{m}$, is rigidly fixed at both ends against translation and rotation. Its long axis (length $L_0$) is defined as the $x$-axis. The bar sits inside a long solenoid whose axis aligns with $x$; the interior magnetic flux density is uniform and parallel to $x$ at all times. The bar forms the resistive element in a series $LCR$ circuit, connected via ideal, thermally insulated leads. At $t=0$, a pre-charged capacitor of capacitance $C = 100 \times 10^{-6}~\rm{F}$ and voltage $V_0 = 2.00 \times 10^4~\rm{V}$ is switched into series with an inductor $L = 25 \times 10^{-6}~\rm{H}$ and the bar. The circuit current $I(t)$ is defined positive in the clockwise direction. At $t=0$, $I(0) = 0$. The apparatus operates in an evacuated, perfectly adiabatic enclosure; the entire bar is initially at uniform temperature $T_0 = 300~\text{K}$. Throughout, the bar remains spatially uniform in temperature, field, and magnetization. Neglect mechanical vibration, gravity, and all forms of energy exchange except those explicitly described. All quantities are in SI units unless noted. 

1. \textbf{Electrical dynamics:} The loop obeys 
\begin{equation*}
L \frac{dI}{dt} + R(T) I + \frac{1}{C} \int_0^t I(t') dt' = V_0
\end{equation*}
where $R(T)$ is the resistance of the bar, which varies linearly with temperature as:
\begin{equation*}
R(T) = \frac{\rho_{e,0} L_0}{w h} \left[1 + \alpha_R (T-T_0)\right]
\end{equation*}
The initial resistivity is $\rho_{e,0} = 6.0 \times 10^{-7}~\Omega\,\text{m}$ and $\alpha_R = 1.5 \times 10^{-3}~\text{K}^{-1}$.

2. \textbf{Magnetic field:} The solenoid has $N = 9500$ turns per meter and carries the current $I(t)$ through the circuit, creating an axial uniform field through the bar given by\n$B(t) = \mu_0 N I(t)$, with $\mu_0 = 4\pi \times 10^{-7}~\rm{T}~\rm{m/A}$. 

3. \textbf{Magnetic equation of state:} The bar’s uniform magnetization $M(t)$ (in $\text{A/m}$) satisfies the mean-field Weiss model:
\begin{equation*}
M = n \mu_B \tanh\left[ \frac{\mu_B}{k_B T} \left( B + \lambda_W \mu_0 M \right) \right]
\end{equation*}
where 
$n = 4.20 \times 10^{28}~\rm{m}^{-3}$ (number density of moments), 
$\mu_B = 9.27401 \times 10^{-24}~\text{J/T}$ (Bohr magneton), 
$\lambda_W = 950$, 
$k_B = 1.380649 \times 10^{-23}~\text{J/K}$.

4. \textbf{Thermal dynamics:} The bar’s temperature obeys
\begin{equation*}
M_{\rm{bar}} c_p \frac{dT}{dt} = I^2 R(T) - \mu_0 T V_{\rm{bar}} \left( \frac{\partial M}{\partial T} \right|_{B} \frac{dB}{dt}
\end{equation*}
where $M_{\rm{bar}} = \rho_m L_0 w h$ is the bar mass, $V_{\rm{bar}} = L_0 w h$ its volume, 
$\rho_m = 9210~\text{kg/m}^3$, $c_p = 330~\text{J}\cdot\text{kg}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}$, and $\left.\frac{\partial M}{\partial T}\right|_B$ is computed by differentiating the implicit Weiss equation with all variables defined above, at fixed $B$.

5. \textbf{Longitudinal strain:} The total axial strain is $\epsilon(t) = \alpha_{\rm{th}} (T(t)-T_0) + \kappa M(t)^2$, with $\alpha_{\rm{th}} = 12 \times 10^{-6}~\text{K}^{-1}$. The bulk magnetostrictive strain coupling is $\kappa = 2.50 \times 10^{-11}~(\text{A}\,\text{m}^{-1})^{-2}$ (ensuring $\epsilon$ dimensionless when $M$ in $\text{A/m}$).

6. \textbf{Axial stress:} The physically correct stress within the clamped bar is $\sigma(t) = -Y \epsilon(t)$, with $Y = 5.00 \times 10^{10}~\text{Pa}$, i.e., both heating and magnetostriction generate thermal expansion and positive magnetostrictive extension, but, with fixed ends, both produce compressive stresses. The sign convention is that $\sigma > 0$ is compressive.

7. \textbf{Buckling criterion:} Buckling initiates when $\sigma(t)$ first equals the Euler critical compressive stress for a fixed-fixed rectangular bar about the axis of minimum second moment (the $z$-axis, i.e., buckling out of plane of the thin face), given by
\begin{equation*}
\sigma_{\rm{crit}} = \frac{\pi^2 Y}{(K L_0)^2} I_{\rm{min}} / A
\end{equation*}
where $K = 0.5$ (effective length factor for fixed–fixed ends), $I_{\rm{min}} = w h^3 / 12$ is the minimum area moment (about $z$), and $A = w h$ is the cross-sectional area. Poisson's ratio effects are neglected.

\textbf{Parameters Summary:}
\begin{align*}
L_0 &= 0.250~\text{m} & w &= 0.0200~\text{m} & h &= 0.00500~\text{m} \\
Y &= 5.00 \times 10^{10}~\rm{Pa} & \rho_m &= 9210~\rm{kg/m}^3 & c_p &= 330~\rm{J\,kg}^{-1}\rm{K}^{-1} \\
\alpha_{\rm{th}} &= 12 \times 10^{-6}~\rm{K}^{-1} & \kappa &= 2.50 \times 10^{-11}~(\rm{A\,m}^{-1})^{-2} & \rho_{e,0} &= 6.00 \times 10^{-7}~\Omega \rm{m} \\
\alpha_R &= 1.5 \times 10^{-3}~\rm{K}^{-1} & N &= 9500~\rm{turns/m} & C &= 1.00 \times 10^{-4}~\rm{F} \\
L &= 2.50 \times 10^{-5}~\rm{H} & V_0 &= 2.00 \times 10^4~\rm{V} & T_0 &= 300~\rm{K} \\
\mu_0 &= 4\pi \times 10^{-7}~\rm{T\,m/A} & k_B &= 1.380649 \times 10^{-23}~\rm{J/K} & \mu_B &= 9.27401 \times 10^{-24}~\rm{J/T} \\
n &= 4.20 \times 10^{28}~\rm{m}^{-3} & \lambda_W &= 950 & & 
\end{align*}

\textbf{Problem:} 
Find, to four significant digits, the precise time $t_{\rm{buckle}}$ (in $\rm{s}$) after $t=0$ at which the compressive axial stress in the bar, $\sigma(t)$, first equals or exceeds the critical buckling stress $\sigma_{\rm{crit}}$ as defined above. Neglect all other forms of instability.

\textbf{Answer:} Enter $t_{\rm{buckle}}$ in seconds ($\rm{s}$).",
